# Adversarial Image Detection via Feature Consistency in Vision Transformers

Post-hoc adversarial example detection without retraining the model. The core insight is that adversarial perturbations are fragile — small benign transformations (blur, noise, rotation) cause large internal feature shifts in adversarial images but not in clean images. We extract multi-layer feature consistency scores from a pretrained ViT and train a meta-classifier to distinguish clean vs. adversarial inputs.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Dataset size trade-off**: CIFAR-10 has 10k test images. Generating adversarial examples for all of them with 2 attacks × 3 transformations is computationally expensive. I plan to use a **subset of 1,000 images** (100 per class) from the test set to keep initial experiments fast. Should I use more?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **ViT input resolution**: ViT-B/16 expects 224×224 input. CIFAR-10 images are 32×32, so they will be **upscaled via bilinear interpolation**. This is standard practice but worth noting — the adversarial perturbations are generated at 32×32 resolution and then upscaled.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Which transformer layers to hook?** ViT-B/16 has 12 transformer blocks. I plan to hook **layers 3, 6, 9, and 11** (early, mid, late, and final) giving 4 layers × 2 metrics (L2, cosine) × 3 transformations = **24-dimensional feature vector**. Let me know if you prefer different layers or more/fewer.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Attack parameters**: For FGSM I'll use `ε = 8/255`. For PGD I'll use `ε = 8/255, α = 2/255, steps = 7`. These are standard settings. Confirm if you want different values.

